<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910122-0090</DOCNO><DOCID>910122-0090.</DOCID><HL>   TWA Announces Layoffs,   Cuts in Overseas Service</HL><DATE>01/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   TWA</CO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   MT. KISCO, N.Y. -- Trans World Airlines yesterday said itis laying off as many as 2,500 employees, or about 8% of itswork force, as part of a sizable cutback in its overseasservice, said Mark Buckstein, general counsel at TWA.   The service cut, as previously reported, involves areduction of about 50% of the carrier's internationalcapacity. It comes in response to a sharp drop in overseastravel in the wake of the Persian Gulf war.</LP><TEXT>   The actions represent the first extensive reduction inoverseas service by a U.S. carrier since the war started.Fears of terrorist attacks against airliners has partlyprompted a sharp decline in advance bookings.   As reported, the employee reduction includes furloughingabout 1,360, or 19%, of its flight attendants and at least100 pilots. TWA has a total of about 30,000 employees.   The schedule and employee cuts come on the heels ofearlier reductions prompted by a steep increase in jet fuelprices following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. Fuel costs arethe airline's second-largest expense after labor costs.</TEXT></DOC>